## Vercel Web Analytics Implementation

Successfully implemented Vercel Web Analytics for the PQCDSME Dashboard project.

### Changes Made

#### 1. Package Installation
- Added `@vercel/analytics` (v2.0.1) to project dependencies
- Updated `package.json` to include the new dependency

#### 2. Analytics Integration
- Modified `src/main.tsx` to inject Vercel Analytics tracking
- Added import: `import { inject } from '@vercel/analytics';`
- Called `inject()` before rendering the React app

### Implementation Details

This project uses **Vite + React**, so I followed the Vite-specific instructions from the official Vercel documentation:
- Fetched latest installation guide from https://vercel.com/docs/analytics/quickstart
- Used the `inject()` method in `main.tsx` as recommended for Vite projects
- This is different from React apps (which use `<Analytics />` component) or Next.js apps (which have framework-specific imports)

### Files Modified
- `artifacts/pqcdsme-dashboard/package.json` - Added @vercel/analytics dependency
- `artifacts/pqcdsme-dashboard/src/main.tsx` - Added analytics injection
- `pnpm-lock.yaml` - Updated lock file with new dependencies

### Verification Steps Completed
✅ Package installed successfully with pnpm
✅ Build completed without errors (`pnpm run build`)
✅ TypeScript typecheck passed with no errors (`pnpm run typecheck`)
✅ Lock file updated to ensure consistent dependencies

### Next Steps for Deployment
To enable analytics tracking in production:
1. Deploy the application to Vercel
2. Enable Web Analytics in the Vercel dashboard (Analytics section)
3. Verify tracking by checking the browser Network tab for analytics requests
4. View analytics data in the Vercel dashboard after users visit the site

### Notes
- Analytics tracking will automatically start once the app is deployed to Vercel
- The `inject()` function loads the analytics script asynchronously
- No additional configuration is required for basic page view tracking
- Data will be available in the Vercel dashboard after deployment
